'''Giovani Lo Celso''' (born 9 April 1996) is an Argentine professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] for [[La Liga]] club [[Real Betis]] and the [[Argentina national football team|Argentina national team]].<ref name="soccerway">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/giovani-lo-celso/392369/|title=G. Lo Celso|website=Soccerway|access-date=2 December 2015}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Rosario Central===
Lo Celso is a youth product of [[Rosario Central]]. He made his [[Argentine Primera División|league debut]] at 19 July 2015 against [[Club Atlético Vélez Sarsfield|Vélez Sarsfield]] in a 0–0 home draw.<ref name="soccerway2">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/07/19/argentina/primera-division/club-atletico-rosario-central/club-atletico-velez-sarsfield/1978392/|title=Rosario Central vs. Velez Sarsfield |publisher=Soccerway |date=19 July 2015 |access-date=19 July 2015}}</ref> On 28 February 2016, Lo Celso scored his first Rosario Central goal in a 3–0 victory over [[Club Atlético Colón|Colón]], netting Rosario's first in the 6th minute.<ref name="soccerway3">{{Cite news |title=Colón vs. Rosario Central |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/02/28/argentina/primera-division/colon-de-santa-fe/club-atletico-rosario-central/2182954/ |publisher=Soccerway |date=28 February 2016 |access-date=26 July 2016}}</ref> He then went on to score his second of the campaign in a 3–2 defeat to Vélez Sarsfield on 10 April 2016.<ref name="soccerway4">{{Cite news |title=Rosario Central vs. Vélez Sarsfield |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/04/10/argentina/primera-division/club-atletico-rosario-central/club-atletico-velez-sarsfield/2183027/ |publisher=Soccerway |date=10 April 2016 |access-date=26 July 2016}}</ref>

===Paris Saint-Germain===
On 26 July 2016, Lo Celso joined French giants [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] on a five-year deal until 2021, for a fee around the margin of £8.5m.<ref name="Giovani Lo Celso signs five-year contract with Paris Saint-Germain">{{Cite news |title=Giovani Lo Celso signs five-year contract with Paris Saint-Germain |url=http://www.psg.fr/en/News/003001/Article/76319/Giovani-Lo-Celso-signs-five-year-contract-with-Paris-Saint-Germain |publisher=Paris Saint-Germain F.C. |date=26 July 2016 |access-date=26 July 2016 |archive-date=28 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160728110723/http://www.psg.fr/en/News/003001/Article/76319/Giovani-Lo-Celso-signs-five-year-contract-with-Paris-Saint-Germain |url-status=dead }}</ref> He remained at Rosario Central on loan until 31 December 2016.<ref name="Giovani Lo Celso signs five-year contract with Paris Saint-Germain"/> He made his debut for the French side on 5 April 2017 in a [[Coupe de France]] quarter final game against [[US Avranches]]. He replaced [[Adrien Rabiot]] in the 63rd minute of a 4–0 away win.<ref name="soccerway5">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/04/05/france/coupe-de-france/us-avranches/paris-saint-germain-fc/2422159/|title=Avranches vs. PSG |publisher=Soccerway |date=5 April 2017 |access-date=9 April 2017}}</ref>

Lo Celso came on and assisted for [[Dani Alves]]’ goal in the UEFA Champions League match against [[Celtic FC]] to make the scoreline 7–1. He scored his first goal for PSG in a 3–2 [[Coupe de la Ligue]] win against [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]] on 30 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42877527|title=Kylian Mbappe: Paris St-Germain forward sent off against Rennes|publisher=[[BBC]] |date=30 January 2018 |access-date=31 January 2018}}</ref>

On 8 May 2018, he scored as PSG won 2–0 against [[Les Herbiers VF]] to clinch the [[2017–18 Coupe de France|2017–18]] [[Coupe de France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/43949707|title=French Cup final - PSG beat Les Herbiers|publisher=BBC Sport|author=Emlyn Begley|date=8 May 2018|access-date=4 June 2018}}</ref>

===Real Betis===
On 31 August 2018, Lo Celso joined [[La Liga]] side [[Real Betis]] on a season-long loan with an option to buy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.psg.fr/teams/first-team/content/giovani-lo-celso-loaned-to-real-betis|title=Giovani Lo Celso loaned to Real Betis|publisher=Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|date=31 August 2018|access-date=31 August 2018}}</ref> Betis triggered this option on 16 April 2019 and Lo Celso joined the club on a permanent basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.onefootball.com/%f0%9f%9a%a8-real-betis-confirm-giovani-lo-celso-signing-from-psg/|title=Real Betis confirm Giovani Lo Celso signing from PSG|work=Onefootball English|date=16 April 2019|access-date=16 April 2019|archive-date=9 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109144758/https://en.onefootball.com/%F0%9F%9A%A8-real-betis-confirm-giovani-lo-celso-signing-from-psg/|url-status=dead}}</ref> During his time at the club, Lo Celso made 46 appearances in all competitions, scoring 16 goals.<ref name="soccerway"/>

===Tottenham Hotspur===
On 8 August 2019, Lo Celso signed for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on a season-long loan with an option to buy, after a long summer of speculation over his future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49283542|title=Tottenham sign winger Ryan Sessegnon for £25m and midfielder Giovani lo Celso on loan|work=BBC News|date=8 August 2019|access-date=8 August 2019}}</ref> He made his debut for Tottenham as a late substitute in the second [[Premier League]] match of the season against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] that ended 2–2, a match notable for a controversy over [[Video assistant referee|VAR]] and a new rule on handball introduced that season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/aug/17/manchester-city-v-tottenham-hotspur-premier-league-live |title=Manchester City 2-2 Tottenham Hotspur: Premier League – as it happened |first=Scott|last= Murray|date= 17 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49388102 |title=Premier League handball: Is new rule spot-on or misguided? |date=18 August 2019 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=19 August 2019 }}</ref>

After three substitute appearances for the club, Lo Celso injured his hip while on international duty for Argentina.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/september/lo-celso-injury-update/|title=Lo Celso injury update|work=Tottenham Hotspur|language=en|date=10 September 2019 |access-date=14 September 2019}}</ref> After returning from injury, he made his first start for Tottenham, scoring his first goal for the club that kicked off a 4–0 win over [[Red Star Belgrade]] in the [[2019–20 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], which was the first away win for Tottenham in six months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/tottenham-vs-crvena-zvedza-uefa-champions-league-2019-lo-celso-red-star-belgrade-a9188756.html |title=Giovani Lo Celso shows Tottenham's future without Christian Eriksen may not be as bleak as feared |first=Peter|last=Hall |date=7 November 2019 |work=The Independent |access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> On 14 January 2020, Lo Celso scored the opening goal in a 2–1 win for Spurs against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] in the [[The Football Association Challenge Cup|FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51091957 |title=Tottenham Hotspur 2 - 1 Middlesbrough |date= 14 January 2020|work=BBC Sport|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref>

Lo Celso's contract was made permanent on 28 January 2020 with the new deal running until the summer of 2025.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2020/january/lo-celso-transfer-confirmed-eriksen-to-inter/ |title=Lo Celso transfer confirmed / Eriksen to Inter |date=28 January 2020|work=Tottenham Hotspur|access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref>

In the [[2020–21 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2020–21 season]], Lo Celso scored his first goals of the season when he netted a brace in the 7–2 win against [[Maccabi Haifa F.C.|Maccabi Haifa]] in a [[2020–21 UEFA Europa League qualifying phase and play-off round#Play-off round|Europa League play-off]] match.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.football.london/tottenham-hotspur-fc/fixtures-results/tottenham-player-ratings-harry-kane-19034471 |title=Tottenham player ratings: Harry Kane the hat-trick hero as Steven Bergwijn and Lo Celso dazzle |work=Football.london |first=Alasdair |last=Gold |date=1 October 2020 }}</ref> On 21 November 2020, Lo Celso scored his first Premier League goal, 35 seconds after coming on as a substitute in the match against Manchester City, which helped secure a 2–0 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54941200 |title=Tottenham Hotspur 2 : 0 Manchester City |first=Phil |last=McNulty |work=BBC Sport |date=21 November 2020}}</ref>

====Loan to Villarreal====
On 31 January 2022, Lo Celso joined [[La Liga]] club [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] on loan until the end of the [[2021–22 La Liga|2021–22]] season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Giovani Lo Celso is a Yellow!|url=https://villarrealcf.es/en/news/item/33220-giovani-lo-celso-is-a-yellow |publisher=Villarreal CF |date=31 January 2022|access-date=31 January 2022}}</ref> On 14 August 2022, he rejoined Villarreal on loan for the [[2022–23 La Liga|2022–23]] season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62544186 |title=Giovani lo Celso: Spurs midfielder joins Villarreal on loan |work=BBC Sport |date=14 August 2022 }}</ref> In November 2022, Lo Celso suffered a hamstring injury, which was successfully operated by surgeon Lasse Lempainen in [[Turku]], Finland.<ref>[https://www.iltalehti.fi/jalkapallo/a/79179520-994c-490d-830d-3b8f22646dd4 Argentiinan jalkapallotähti leikattiin Turussa], [[Iltalehti]], 12 November 2022</ref>

====Return to Tottenham====
On 26 November 2023, Lo Celso made his first Premier League start for Tottenham in over two years, scoring Tottenham's only goal in a 2–1 defeat to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Villa fight back to win as Spurs remember Venables |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67466092 |access-date=2023-12-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Smith |first=Dom |date=2023-11-27 |title=Lo Celso must seize his second chance to become a Spurs success story |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham-giovani-lo-celso-postecoglou-b1123131.html |access-date=2023-12-08 |website=Evening Standard |language=en}}</ref> In the following game, Lo Celso scored his second goal of the [[2023–24 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2023–24 season]] in a 3–3 draw against Manchester City.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/13018982/man-city-3-3-tottenham-dejan-kulusevskis-90th-minute-equaliser-earns-spurs-amazing-draw-in-thrilling-game |title=Tottenham Hotspur 3 : 3 Manchester City |first= Adam |last=Bate |work=Sky Sports |date=3 December 2023}}</ref>

===Return to Real Betis===
On 30 August 2024, before the transfer window closed, Lo Celso departed Tottenham Hotspur and returned back to [[Real Betis]], signing a four-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |title=El Real Betis y el Tottenham Hotspur acuerdan el traspaso de Giovani Lo Celso |url=https://www.realbetisbalompie.es/noticias/actualidad/el-real-betis-y-el-tottenham-hotspur-acuerdan-el-traspaso-de-giovani-lo-celso-30469 |publisher=Real Betis Balompié |access-date=31 August 2024 |date=31 August 2024 }}</ref> He made his first notable impact after his return on 18 September 2024, scoring twice in a 2–1 league victory against Getafe, including a penalty and a deflected strike.<ref>{{cite web |title=Giovani Lo Celso masterclass secures victory for Real Betis against Getafe|url=https://www.football-espana.net/2024/09/18/giovani-lo-celso-masterclass-secures-victory-for-real-betis-against-getafe|publisher=Football España|access-date=18 September 2024 |date=18 September 2024 }}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Due to some impressive performances at Rosario Central, Lo Celso earned a call-up to the [[Argentina national under-23 football team|Argentina U23]] squad for the [[2016 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Olympic Football Tournament Rio 2016 - Argentina |url=https://www.fifa.com/mensolympic/teams/team=1889265/players.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727204857/http://www.fifa.com/mensolympic/teams/team=1889265/players.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 July 2016 |publisher=FIFA |access-date=26 July 2016}}</ref> On 4 August 2016, Lo Celso made his Argentina U23 debut in a 2–0 defeat against [[Portugal Olympic football team|Portugal]], replacing [[Cristian Espinoza]] in the 72nd minute.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Portugal U23 vs. Argentina U23 |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/lineups?gameId=447188 |publisher=ESPN |date=4 August 2016 |access-date=19 August 2016}}</ref>{{Better source needed|reason=Secondary source|date=May 2024}}

===Senior===
[[File:Giovani Lo Celso (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Lo Celso warming up for [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in 2017]]
On 11 November 2017, Lo Celso debuted for the Argentine senior squad in a 1–0 victory over [[Russia national football team|Russia]] as a starter, only to be replaced by [[Alejandro Darío Gómez|Alejandro Gómez]] in the 59th minute.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Ante Russia, Selección Argentina Empieza Nueva Etapa|url=https://www.catamarcactual.com.ar/deportes/2017/11/11/ante-rusia-seleccin-argentina-empieza-nueva-etapa-145979.html|website=Catamarc Actual|date=11 November 2017|language=es|quote=Entre otras novedades, figura una prueba de fuego para Germán Pezzella como defensor central, mientras que también aparecerá en el equipo el volante Matías Kranevitter y será el debut como titular del talentoso mediocampista Giovani Lo Celso del PSG de Francia.|trans-quote=Among other newcomers, there is a litmus test for Germán Pezzella as a central defender, while midfielder Matías Kranevitter will also appear in the team and it will be the debut as a starter for the talented midfielder Giovani Lo Celso of French club PSG.}}</ref>

In May 2018, Lo Celso was named in Argentina's preliminary 35-man [[Argentina national football team|squad]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia;<ref>{{cite web|first=Stephen|last=Crawford|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad {{!}} Final 23-man lists|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=4 June 2018}}</ref> he was later included in the final 23-man selection for the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad|publisher=Goal|access-date=25 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/icardi-cut-from-argentinas-23-man-world-cup-squad/lo0f6fig55ih1jh7w9v4enau6 |title=Icardi cut from Argentina's 23-man World Cup squad|website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|publisher=[[Perform Group]]|date=21 May 2018}}</ref>

In May 2019, Lo Celso was included in [[Lionel Scaloni]]'s final 23-man Argentina squad for the [[2019 Copa América]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Messi Leads Argentina's Copa America Squad; Icardi Omitted|url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2019/05/21/argentina-copa-america-squad-roster-messi-aguero-dybala-scaloni|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=21 May 2019 |access-date=21 May 2019 }}</ref> On 28 June, in the quarter-finals of the tournament, Lo Celso scored Argentina's second goal in a 2–0 victory over [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]], which enabled his team to advance to the semi-finals of the competition.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tsn.ca/argentina-beats-venezuela-faces-brazil-in-copa-america-semi-1.1330093 |title=Argentina beats Venezuela, faces Brazil in Copa América semi|website=[[TSN Radio]]|date=28 June 2019 |access-date=29 June 2019 }}</ref>

In June 2021, Lo Celso was once again included in Scaloni's final Argentina 28-man squad for the [[2021 Copa América]], which the team eventually won. He also played against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in the [[CONMEBOL–UEFA Cup of Champions|Finalissima]], which Argentina won 3–0 at [[Wembley Stadium]], England on 1 June 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Italy 0-3 Argentina: South American champions cruise to Finalissima glory|url=https://www.uefa.com/finalissima/news/0276-1549514538ab-f782a73cf733-1000--italy-0-3-argentina-south-american-champions-cruise-to-finaliss/|website=[[UEFA]]|date=1 June 2021|access-date=16 December 2022}}</ref> He was not included in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] squad, due to a hamstring injury.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Karim Benzema, Sadio Mane, Jesus Corona: 10 stars ruled out of 2022 World Cup through injury|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37634059/karim-benzema-sadio-mane-10-injured-stars-ruled-2022-world-cup|website=[[ESPN]]|date=20 November 2022}}</ref>

After recovering from his injury, he returned to the team, being a usual in Scaloni's call-ups despite not having much game time in [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]]. On 21 November 2023, in a game for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] against Brazil at the [[Maracanã Stadium|Estadio Maracana]], he provided an assist from a corner kick to [[Nicolás Otamendi]] in what would be a 1-0 away win, which became the first time the latter had lost a qualifiers game in home condition.

In June 2024, Lo Celso was included in Lionel Scaloni's final 26-man Argentina squad for the [[2024 Copa América]]. On 14 July, in the [[2024 Copa América final|final]] against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]], he came off the bench in the 97th minute of extra-time replacing [[Enzo Fernández]]. In the 112th minute, he provided the assist to [[Lautaro Martínez]] that ended up in the goal that would crown Argentina champions.

==Personal life==
Born and raised in Argentina, Lo Celso also holds an Italian passport due to his Italian heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/2859651/paris-saint-germain-move-appealing-to-rosarios-giovani-lo-celso-father|title=Paris Saint-Germain move 'appealing' to Rosario's Giovani Lo Celso - father|work=ESPN |first=Mark |last=Rodden |date=27 April 2016 |access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> His younger brother [[Francesco Lo Celso|Francesco]] is also a professional footballer and currently plays for [[Estudiantes de Río Cuarto|Estudiantes RC]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Giovani Lo Celso Childhood Story Plus Untold Biography Facts|work=LifeBogger |date=26 January 2020 |url=https://lifebogger.com/giovani-lo-celso-childhood-story-plus-untold-biography-facts/|access-date=2 March 2020 |last1=Hendrix |first1=Hale }}</ref>

